T1  - "Let's beat cancer together": A hidden curriculum of medical gentrification on 
SP  - 118167
AB  - Literature on medical gentrification has examined the role of hospitals in the  displacement of nearby low-income residents. This paper follows a case of medical  gentrification in which a public school was demolished to construct a university  cancer center. We describe the process through which spaces earmarked for  redevelopment become portrayed as frontiers of biomedical innovation. Through  collaborative, visual, and auto-ethnography, we demonstrate how developers  instill a hidden curriculum of medical gentrification through visual and  discursive devices such as advertisements, ceremonies, and urban planning efforts  that conceal local histories of displacement, reinforce racial and economic  segregation, and elevate biomedical innovation as a community good. Ultimately,  the hidden curriculum of medical gentrification constrains possible narratives of  collective futures, privileging the expansion of biomedical infrastructure at the  expense of the local community.
