Y1  - 2019
T1  - Student Evaluation of Interprofessional Experiences between Medical and Graduate 
AB  - BACKGROUND: Interprofessional education (IPE) has fostered increased  collaboration and appreciation for different disciplines among health  professionals but has yet to be established in a translational research setting.  Interprofessional experiences (IPEx) implemented early in student training could  increase translational research productivity. METHODS AND FINDINGS: Ten students  involved in an IPE curriculum wrote autoethnographic accounts that were coded and  emergent themes were grouped through constant comparative analysis. IPE led to  improvements in communication, trust, appreciation, and an increased desire to  seek IPE in future careers. Challenges included administrative barriers and  interpersonal conflicts. CONCLUSIONS: Participants found IPE beneficial to their  careers and developed a respect for each other's discipline. To implement IPE,  institutions should consider possible administrative challenges and inclusion of  conflict management training.
