T1  - Recursive Health Care Structures and Choice in the Manner of Our Dying: An 
SP  - 452-65
AB  - Science has shaped our understanding of the diseases we are diagnosed with.  Medical treatment has transformed their natural courses. The law has married  medical knowledge and experience to the legal competence of physicians to make  ultimate decisions for the patient at the end of life. When it is our time to  die, we will confront a pre-structured health care landscape affording some  courses of action while limiting others. In this article, I provide an  auto-ethnographic account of the dying of one woman, my wife, diagnosed with  ovarian cancer. It speaks of our meeting with oncology, her refusal of aggressive  treatment, and the palliative care allies we found for her way of dying. It also  speaks of the opportunities for choice in dying that emerge when participants in  the care collective accept that one of them must die while the others live on.
